#X text 161 129 By default we have a linear tracking in pitch difference. But you can use exponential factors. An exponential factor of '1' or '0' is linear and '0' is the default. Values greater than one expand the tracking amount \, where A semitone difference is much lower than higher intervals. Regardless of the exponential factor \, if you have a tracking amount of 100% \, an octave higher or lower will still be the same as linear (respectively '2' and '0.5'). Exponential values lower than 1 have the opposite behaviour. Note that below and above the reference point(s) we have a mirrored behaviour., f 74;
#X floatatom 79 336 6 0 0 0 - - - 0;
#X obj 36 360 else/keytrack2, f 15;
#X floatatom 123 336 6 0 0 0 - - - 0;
#X msg 62 302 exp \$1 \$1;
#X text 163 233 Hence \, they form a sort of 'S' shaped curve if you have the same value. The plot below is done with a [rescale] object. Of course \, you can set two different values for below and above the reference points., f 37;
#X text 168 326 Changing the amount also affects the overall range of the curve below and above., f 32;
#X text 413 425 You can have negative values \, which will reverse the curves. For instance '1 -1' has a linear rise up to the reference point then it drops decreasing in linear again., f 34;
